Change-Id: I7d3d134aa43b174351a403f5e183a7b87513e20b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/63ae6a82926e84d09e3739d0c9e00cac922d40e0"},{"sha":"76838b4bbba30133eaf9fce67a64b694c2e92e3c","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Add metric to count number of times XlaLaunch is called.

This is similar to the existing tf_function_counter metric, which counts the number of tf.functions created with jit_compile=False and jit_compile=True. The difference is this new metric counts all times XlaLaunch is run, not just compiled, and the new metric counts XlaLaunch usage even if not run with a tf.function. The new metric also has a separate counter per device.

explicit sharding. This includes the outfeed and infeed used by host_callback.

The implementation here uses AssignDevice sharding for both the outfeed and the
infeed. This means that before outfeed, the devices will do an all_gather and
the first device will make the outfeed. The host callback will receive a single
outfeed with the entire array, and is supposed to return the entire array. This
gets sent to the same device that issued to outfeed, which is responsible to
send the respective slices to the other participating devices.

漏洞描述

fastjson采用黑白名单的方法来防御反序列化漏洞，导致当黑客不断发掘新的反序列化Gadgets类时，在autoType关闭的情况下仍然可能可以绕过黑白名单防御机制，造成远程命令执行漏洞。经研究，该漏洞利用门槛较低，可绕过autoType限制，风险影响较大。阿里云应急响应中心提醒fastjson用户尽快采取安全措施阻止漏洞攻击。

影响版本

fastjson <=1.2.68

fastjson sec版本 <= sec9

安全版本

fastjson >=1.2.69

1. Move tf.data service tests to their own subfolder.

3. Rename from "round robin" to "coordinated read". It describes the feature better since with skipping the order isn't necessarily round robin. Followup CLs will complete the rename.

The new metric also has a separate counter per device.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fix divide_no_nan for near-zero complex inputs (#48350).

The Eigen packet `pdiv` operation for complex types divides by the
squared-magnitude of the divisor. If this underflows to zero, the
result is a NaN.  To prevent NaNs, modify condition to check for this,
setting the result to zero if the magnitude-squared of the divisor is
zero.

NOTE: Eigen's underflow behavior for complex division is consistent with both
gcc's implementation and with pytorch.  Clang does special-handling to prevent
such underflows at the expense of additional cycles. If comparing to numpy
built with clang, we may see differing results. We also see different results
when comparing between CPU and GPU due to different handling of subnormals.

Fixes #48350.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fix divide_no_nan for near-zero complex inputs (#48350).

The Eigen packet `pdiv` operation for complex types divides by the
squared-magnitude of the divisor. If this underflows to zero, the
result is a NaN.  To prevent NaNs, modify condition to check for this,
setting the result to zero if the magnitude-squared of the divisor is
zero.

NOTE: Eigen's underflow behavior for complex division is consistent with both
gcc's implementation and with pytorch.  Clang does special-handling to prevent
such underflows at the expense of additional cycles. If comparing to numpy
built with clang, we may see differing results. We also see different results
when comparing between CPU and GPU due to different handling of subnormals.

Fixes #48350.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Fix divide_no_nan for near-zero complex inputs (#48350).

The Eigen packet `pdiv` operation for complex types divides by the
squared-magnitude of the divisor. If this underflows to zero, the
result is a NaN.  To prevent NaNs, modify condition to check for this,
setting the result to zero if the magnitude-squared of the divisor is
zero.

NOTE: Eigen's underflow behavior for complex division is consistent with both
gcc's implementation and with pytorch.  Clang does special-handling to prevent
such underflows at the expense of additional cycles. If comparing to numpy
built with clang, we may see differing results. We also see different results
when comparing between CPU and GPU due to different handling of subnormals.

Fixes #48350.
